Explore global development with R

In this exercise, you will load a filtered gapminder dataset - with a subset of data on global development from 1952 - 2007 in increments of 5 years - to capture the period between the Second World War and the Global Financial Crisis.

Your task: Explore the data and visualise it in both static and animated ways, providing answers and solutions to 7 questions/tasks within this script.

  • Submit to Github this script with solutions and its knitted version.
  • Submit to Brightspace a document with the (1) URL of this script and its knitted version in Github (2) answer of 250 words and a (3) visualisation of the Final Question

# Load necessary libraries
library(dplyr)
library(gapminder)

# Find the five richest countries in 2007 based on GDP per capita
richest_countries <- gapminder %>%
  filter(year == 2007) %>%
  arrange(desc(gdpPercap)) %>%
  head(5)

# Print the five richest countries

Make it move!

The comparison would be easier if we had the two graphs together, animated. We have a lovely tool in R to do this: the gganimate package. Beware that there may be other packages your operating system needs in order to glue interim images into an animation or video. Read the messages when installing the package.

Also, there are two ways of animating the gapminder ggplot.

Option 1: Animate using transition_states()

The first step is to create the object-to-be-animated

anim <- ggplot(gapminder, aes(gdpPercap, lifeExp, size = pop)) +
  geom_point(aes(color=continent)) +
  scale_x_log10()  # convert x to log scale
anim

# Set option to disable scientific notation
options(scipen = 999)

…

This plot collates all the points across time. The next step is to split it into years and animate it. This may take some time, depending on the processing power of your computer (and other things you are asking it to do). Beware that the animation might appear in the bottom right ‘Viewer’ pane, not in this rmd preview. You need to knit the document to get the visual inside an html file.

anim + transition_states(year, 
                      transition_length = 1,
                      state_length = 1)

…

Notice how the animation moves jerkily, ‘jumping’ from one year to the next 12 times in total. This is a bit clunky, which is why it’s good we have another option.

Option 2 Animate using transition_time()

This option smooths the transition between different ‘frames’, because it interpolates and adds transitional years where there are gaps in the timeseries data.

anim2 <- ggplot(gapminder, aes(gdpPercap, lifeExp, size = pop)) +
  geom_point(aes(color=continent)) +
  scale_x_log10() + # convert x to log scale
  transition_time(year)+
  labs(
    title = 'Global GDP per Capita and Life Expectancy Over Time',  # Static title
    subtitle = 'Year: {frame_time}',  # Dynamic subtitle with year (updated for each frame)
    x = 'GDP per Capita', 
    y = 'Life Expectancy'
  ) +
  transition_time(year) +  # Animate over the year
  ease_aes('linear')  # Linear transition
anim2

options(scipen = 999)

The much smoother movement in Option 2 will be much more noticeable if you add a title to the chart, that will page through the years corresponding to each frame.

Now, choose one of the animation options and get it to work. You may need to troubleshoot your installation of gganimate and other packages

animation 2002 to 2007:

library(ggplot2)
library(gganimate)
library(dplyr)

# Filter for years 2002 to 2007
gapminder_filtered <- gapminder %>%
  filter(year >= 2002 & year <= 2007)

# Create the animated plot
anim0207 <- ggplot(gapminder_filtered, aes(gdpPercap, lifeExp, size = pop)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = continent)) +
  scale_x_log10() +  # Convert x-axis to log scale
  transition_time(year) +  # Animate over the years 2002-2007
  labs(
    title = 'Global GDP per Capita and Life Expectancy Over Time',  
    subtitle = 'Year: {frame_time}',  # Dynamic subtitle showing the year
    x = 'GDP per Capita', 
    y = 'Life Expectancy'
  ) +
  ease_aes('linear')  # Smooth linear transition
anim0207

Plot from 2002 and 2007:

library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)

# Filter dataset for 2002 and 2007
gapminder_filtered <- gapminder %>%
  filter(year %in% c(2002, 2007))

# Create the plot
ggplot(gapminder_filtered, aes(x = gdpPercap, y = lifeExp, size = pop, color = continent)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.7) +  # Semi-transparent points
  scale_x_log10() +  # Log scale for GDP per capita
  facet_wrap(~year) +  # Create separate panels for 2002 and 2007
  labs(
    title = "GDP per Capita and Life Expectancy (2002 vs 2007)",
    x = "GDP per Capita (log scale)",
    y = "Life Expectancy",
    color = "Continent",
    size = "Population"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()  # Clean theme

Bar plot for 2002 and 2007:


``` r
library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)

# Filter dataset for 2002 and 2007, then summarize by continent
gapminder_filtered <- gapminder %>%
  filter(year %in% c(2002, 2007)) %>%
  group_by(continent, year) %>%
  summarise(avg_gdpPercap = mean(gdpPercap), .groups = 'drop')

# Create block diagram (bar chart)
ggplot(gapminder_filtered, aes(x = continent, y = avg_gdpPercap, fill = continent)) +
  geom_col(position = "dodge") +  # Creates grouped bars for 2002 and 2007
  facet_wrap(~year) +  # Separate plots for 2002 and 2007
  scale_y_log10() +  # Log scale for better visualization
  labs(
    title = "Average GDP per Capita by Continent (2002 vs 2007)",
    x = "Continent",
    y = "Average GDP per Capita (log scale)",
    fill = "Continent"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

When defining whether the world is a better place today than in the year we were born, we use the year 2002. We define “better” by gdp per capita, which is defined as: “Average economic output per person in a country or region per year”. This indicates the wealth of the citizens in each country. The newest data from gapminder is from 2007, and we will therefore compare 2002 to 2007. We are aware that the information of 2007 is outdated in comparison to 2025, but due to trouble with uploading the newest data we have to work with what we have.

When we look at the comparison between 2002 and 2007, we can see minor improvements for all continents with similar rise in GDP per capita. The animation confirms this statement when showing the movement towards a higher GDP per. capita. You can see from both the graph and animation that Europe and Oceania have a significally higher GDP per capita than Africa both in 2002 and 2007. So there is a general incline for all, but the division between Europe, Oceania and Africa remains roughly the same. So has the world gotten any better in five years? Regarding to the wealth of the citizens, yes, a bit. But there is still inequality to be seen between Africa and Europe, Oceania.
